---
export const prerender = true;
import "../styles/global.css";
import Masthead from "../components/Masthead.astro";
import Lede from "../components/Lede.astro";
import Itch from "../components/Itch.astro";
import WhatItIsnt from "../components/WhatItIsnt.astro";
import Colophon from "../components/Colophon.astro";
import WobblyRule from "../components/WobblyRule.astro";
import SubscribeCard from "../components/SubscribeCard.astro";
---
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1" />
    <title>BONK | a workout app i made for myself</title>
    <meta name="description" content="A workout app I built for myself. It's not done." />

    <link rel="icon" href="/favicon-32.png" type="image/png" sizes="32x32" />
    <link rel="icon" href="/favicon-16.png" type="image/png" sizes="16x16" />
    <link rel="apple-touch-icon" href="/apple-touch-icon.png" />

    <meta property="og:title" content="BONK" />
    <meta property="og:description" content="A workout app I built for myself. It's not done." />
    <meta property="og:image" content="https://ridebonk.com/og.png" />
    <meta property="og:type" content="website" />
    <meta property="og:url" content="https://ridebonk.com/" />
    <meta name="twitter:card" content="summary_large_image" />

    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com" />
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin />
    <link
      rel="stylesheet"
      href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Source+Serif+4:wght@700&family=JetBrains+Mono:wght@400;500&display=swap"
    />
  </head>
  <body>
    <main>
      <Masthead />
      <WobblyRule />
      <Lede />
      <WobblyRule />
      <Itch number={1} headline="I wanted an AI coach that wasn't forty bucks a month.">
        <p>
          Zwift, TrainerRoad, and Rouvy are all genuinely good.
          They&apos;re also genuinely not free. And I could never find the
          exact workout I wanted, and sure as shit couldn&apos;t be fucked
          designing one in their editor. I wanted something that watched
          my actual rides, knew my actual fitness, and would write me a
          workout when I told it "give me ninety minutes that won&apos;t
          ruin tomorrow&apos;s gravel". So I built that.
        </p>
        <div slot="figure" class="screenshot-pair">
          <figure class="screenshot-slot">
            <img src="/screenshots/train-picker.png" alt="Train screen with sliders for time, style, legs, and energy" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption class="mono">fig. 1a · tell it what you&apos;ve got</figcaption>
          </figure>
          <figure class="screenshot-slot">
            <img src="/screenshots/workout-ready.png" alt="Generated Easy Spin Recovery Ride workout with coach's rationale" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption class="mono">fig. 1b · it writes you a workout</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
      </Itch>
      <Itch number={2} headline="I wanted to ride a real climb without leaving Australia.">
        <p>
          I wanted to load up the Stelvio, or Alpe d&apos;Huez, or my own
          driveway, on the trainer and ride it. Not a fake race against
          ghosts. Just the gradient profile of a real climb, slotted into
          whatever I was already doing. So I built that too.
        </p>
        <div slot="figure" class="screenshot-pair">
          <figure class="screenshot-slot">
            <img src="/screenshots/climb-ventoux.png" alt="Mont Ventoux climb detail with map and elevation profile" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption class="mono">fig. 2a · Ventoux, on my driveway</figcaption>
          </figure>
          <figure class="screenshot-slot">
            <img src="/screenshots/climb-falls-creek.png" alt="Live climb screen showing Falls Creek Back of Falls in progress with gradient, watts, BPM and gear" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption class="mono">fig. 2b · Falls Creek, mid-climb</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
      </Itch>
      <Itch number={3} headline="I wanted it to not be boring.">
        <p>
          Most cycling apps have the personality of a printer driver. This
          one doesn&apos;t. There are a handful of coach personalities. You
          pick one. The post-ride writeups try to be at least slightly
          interesting. Sometimes they&apos;re at your expense.
          That&apos;s fine.
        </p>
        <div slot="figure" class="screenshot-pair">
          <figure class="screenshot-slot">
            <img src="/screenshots/workout-active.png" alt="In-workout screen with coach Wade telling Reid to chill the fuck out for 60 minutes" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption class="mono">fig. 3a · coach has opinions</figcaption>
          </figure>
          <figure class="screenshot-slot">
            <img src="/screenshots/ride-summary.png" alt="Post-ride summary with coach's comment that Reid went full feral on a recovery spin" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption class="mono">fig. 3b · so does the writeup</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
      </Itch>
      <Itch number={4} headline="I wanted to skip the chest strap on cold mornings.">
        <p>
          Putting on a cold heart rate strap at 5am in winter is one of
          those small daily indignities I built this app to avoid.
          There&apos;s a companion watch app that streams your heart rate
          from your wrist straight into the ride. Pair the watch, hit
          start, ride.
        </p>
        <div slot="figure" class="screenshot-pair">
          <figure class="screenshot-slot">
            <img src="/screenshots/watch-bonk-hr.png" alt="Apple Watch Ultra running BONK showing live heart rate at 142 BPM with the sad banana logo" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption class="mono">fig. 4a · live from the wrist</figcaption>
          </figure>
          <figure class="screenshot-slot">
            <img src="/screenshots/watch-bonk-controls.png" alt="Apple Watch Ultra running BONK in ride mode: heart rate 142 bpm, Connected status, Pause and Skip buttons, full-width End button" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption class="mono">fig. 4b · controls on the wrist</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
      </Itch>
      <Itch number={5} headline="I wanted my Kickr to actually feel like a bike.">
        <p>
          It&apos;s built for smart trainers. Kickr, Tacx, anything that
          speaks Bluetooth. ERG mode for the intervals, gradient
          simulation for the climbs. If you&apos;ve got a Kickr Move with
          virtual gears and a click shifter (and you can even change
          gears from your watch), it talks to that too.
        </p>
        <figure slot="figure" class="screenshot-slot">
          <img src="/screenshots/watch-bonk-shifting.png" alt="Apple Watch Ultra running BONK in sim mode with Shift- and Shift+ buttons for virtual gear changes, plus an End button" loading="lazy" />
          <figcaption class="mono">fig. 5 · shifting from the wrist</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </Itch>
      <Itch number={6} headline="I wanted my iPad free for The Sopranos.">
        <p>
          Bonk runs on the phone. The phone drives the trainer, talks to
          the watch, and shows you the workout. The iPad gets to do what
          an iPad is actually for: another episode of The Sopranos while
          you grind through ninety minutes of threshold.
        </p>
      </Itch>
      <aside class="also">
        <p class="mono also-label">also in there</p>
        <div class="screenshot-pair">
          <figure class="screenshot-slot">
            <img src="/screenshots/history.png" alt="History tab with YTD stats, top efforts, and a list of recent rides" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption class="mono">fig. 7a · history</figcaption>
          </figure>
          <figure class="screenshot-slot">
            <img src="/screenshots/career.png" alt="Career screen with progression levels for each training zone" loading="lazy" />
            <figcaption class="mono">fig. 7b · career levels</figcaption>
          </figure>
        </div>
      </aside>
      <WobblyRule />
      <WhatItIsnt />
      <WobblyRule />
      <SubscribeCard />
      <Colophon />
    </main>

    <style>
      .screenshot-slot {
        margin: 1.5rem 0 0;
        max-width: 220px;
      }
      .screenshot-slot img {
        display: block;
        width: 100%;
        height: auto;
        border: 1px solid var(--color-ink);
        border-radius: 14px;
        box-shadow: 4px 5px 0 rgba(27, 27, 27, 0.08);
        background: #000;
      }
      .screenshot-pair {
        display: flex;
        flex-wrap: wrap;
        gap: 1.25rem 1rem;
        margin: 1.5rem 0 0;
      }
      .also {
        margin: 2.5rem 0 0;
        padding-left: calc(4.5rem + 1rem);
      }
      .also-label {
        margin: 0 0 0.25rem;
        opacity: 0.6;
        font-size: 0.7rem;
      }
      .also .screenshot-pair { margin: 0.5rem 0 0; }
      @media (max-width: 30rem) {
        .also { padding-left: calc(3.2rem + 1rem); }
      }
      .screenshot-pair .screenshot-slot {
        margin: 0;
        flex: 1 1 180px;
        max-width: 220px;
      }
      .screenshot-slot figcaption {
        margin-top: 0.5rem;
        opacity: 0.6;
        font-size: 0.62rem;
        letter-spacing: 0.05em;
      }
    </style>
  </body>
</html>
